<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai To `Vigorously' Develop Rural Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai To `Vigorously' Develop Rural Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1305130794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0840 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1305130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 13 (XINHUA) -- China's leading 
industrial center will make fresh efforts to vigorously develop 
its rural industry this year. 
  Officials at the Administration of Industry in suburban 
Shanghai said they have worked out a plan to foster the leading 
enterprises among rural industrial businesses. 
  A rural enterprise must meet at least one of the following 
three requirements if it wants to be called a "dragon head 
enterprise": output value surpassing 500 million yuan and 
profits amounting to 20 million yuan; delivery of commodities 
for export totalling 10 million U.S. dollars a year; or 
experiencing a net increase of 100 million yuan in the output 
value of products for 1994. 
  The municipality now has 15,000 rural and township 
industrial 
enterprises. Last year these enterprises generated 78.8 billion 
yuan in output value, accounting for a quarter of Shanghai's 
total industrial output value. 
  Experts believe that such a program will bring about 
fundamental changes in the development of Shanghai's rural 
industry. The structure of technological products will be 
gradually adapted to the operation of the city's new economy, 
and a modern enterprise system is being introduced into rural 
industrial enterprises by way of takeover, share participation 
and joint operation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

