<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kissenger Notes China's `Important' Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kissenger Notes China's `Important' Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1405182094 Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1100 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1405182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1100 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Correspondents identified by caption; from the "National </F>
News Hookup" program] 
  [Text] Former U.S. Secretary of State Kissinger, who is 
currently on a visit to Beijing, was interviewed by station 
reporters on the afternoon of 13 May. [video shows a 
correspondent with a microphone in hand sitting across from 
Kissinger; a caption on the bottom of the screen reads: An 
interview with Kissinger by correspondents Gu Yunlong (6253 0061 
7893), Wu Wei (0702 3555), and Xie Li (6200 0500]) 
  [Correspondent] Dr. Kissinger, as a farseeing politician, 
what are your views on China's status and role in the world 
political and economic orders now and in the future? How should 
China proceed to take advantage of the opportunity presented to 
China by the world? 
  [Kissinger, in English fading into Chinese translation] 
First, the new world order will be composed of some influential 
countries: the United States, Japan, China, Russia, Europe, and 
India. These nations interact with one another free of any 
ideological conflicts and share common interests in many areas. 
  China attaches great importance to stability in Asia, does 
not have any territorial designs, and does not have troops 
stationed outside its borders. The United States has no 
territorial designs, either. This can serve as a basis for 
common efforts toward maintaining global peace. 
  China will play an increasingly important role on the world 
stage. Economically, China will grow in importance as an 
exporter; at the same time, it will also become a major 
importer, thus becoming an integral part of the world economy. 
Because the world economy is closely linked with countries of 
the world, China's development will have a direct impact on 
world economic development. China follows with great interest 
countries of the world, which, on the other hand, have shown 
great interest in China. In the next century, China will play 
an even bigger role. 

</TEXT>

