<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tibet Regulations on Mountaineering Explained </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tibet Regulations on Mountaineering Explained </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1205123394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0859 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1205123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lhasa, may 8 (XINHUA) -- Foreign mountaineers can 
climb mountains in Tibet by just filing a written application 
with the local mountaineering association, according to a set of 
new regulations promulgated by the Tibet Autonomous Regional 
Government. 
  They are also required, at the same time, to file 
applications for taking along scientific survey instruments and 
equipment, means of transport, telecommunications and 
photographic equipment and for carrying activities other than 
mountaineering. 
  The set of new regulations, which was adopted by the local 
autonomous regional people's congress Saturday [7 May], applies 
to all mountains and peaks over 5,500 meters in Tibet or on the 
borders and mountain-related activities including mountain 
climbing, adventuring, alpine skiing and gliding and rock 
climbing. 
  The new regulations come into effect on July 1 this year. It 
is the first of its kind governing mountain climbing in the 
Tibet Autonomous Region. 
  The four highest peaks in the world, each topping 8,000 
meters, rise along the border areas of Nepal and Tibet, 
including Mount Qumulangma (Everest). Called the "Roof of the 
World," Tibet has another mount topping 8,000 meters and there 
are thousands of peaks more than 7,000 meters high. 
  Local officials said that some 44 mountains in the 
autonomous 
region have been open to foreigners since 1980. Nearly 6,000 
mountain climbers from 26 countries and regions around the world 
have visited the area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-50138 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi094_p_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-094 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPPCC Group Inspects Hainan's Cultural Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CPPCC Group Inspects Hainan's Cultural Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1605093694 Haikou Hainan People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 2300 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1605093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Haikou Hainan People's Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A 10-member cultural inspection group sent by the 
Education and Culture Committee under the Chinese People's 
Political Consultative Conference [CPPCC] National Committee is 
carrying out a round-the-island tour to inspect Hainan's 
cultural market as of 11 May. On the evening of 10 and 11 May, 
Governor Ruan Chongwu, secretary of the provincial party 
committee; Do Qinglin, deputy secretary of the provincial party 
committee and chairman of the provincial people's congress 
standing committee; Yao Wenxu, chairman of the provincial CPPCC 
committee; Liu Xuebin, member of the provincial party committee 
standing committee, director of the provincial propaganda 
department, and special assistant to the governor; and Hu Kai 
and Lin Mingyu, vice chairmen of the provincial CPPCC committee; 
met with all members of the group in Haikou. 
  Qian Liren -- member of the Standing Committee of the CPPCC 
National Committee, executive deputy director of the CPPCC 
Education and Culture Committee, and former director of RENMIN 
RIBAO -- is chief of the cultural inspection group, while Wang 
Jifu -- member of the Standing Committee of the CPPCC National 
Committee, deputy director of the CPPCC Education and Culture 
Committee, and former vice minister of culture -- is deputy 
chief. Members of the group include Yu Yang, member of the 
CPPCC National Committee, member of the CPPCC Education and 
Culture Committee, and head of the Artists' Theoretical Troupe 
under the Beijing Film Studio; (Chen Duo), member of the CPPCC 
National Committee, member of the CPPCC Education and Culture 
Committee, and deputy director of the Liaison Committee under 
the Central Committee of China Association for Promoting 
Democracy; Li Weikang, member of the CPPCC National Committee, 
member of the CPPCC Education and Culture Committee, and former 
director of the Second Troupe under the China Beijing Opera 
Theater; (Zhao Qing), member of the CPPCC National Committee and 
member of the Executive Committee under Chinese Dancers' 
Association; and others. The 10-member inspection group arrived 
in Haikou from Beijing on the afternoon of 10 May. Lin Mingyu, 
vice chairman of the provincial CPPCC committee, and others met 
the group at the airport. 
  In a meeting hall located on the eighth floor of the 
provincial government office on the morning of 11 May, all 
comrades of the inspection group listened to reports by leaders 
of the provincial cultural and sports department on the 
development of Hainan's cultural market. In the afternoon and 
evening of the same day, members of the group inspected some 
cultural, book and journal, and audio-video markets, as well as 
some amusement places, such as song and dance halls, in the 
Haikou area. On 12 May, they will continue their inspection 
around Haikou. On 13 May, they will start their 
around-the-island inspection of the long cultural corridor along 
the eastern highways. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

