<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Not To Rule Out Ties With Pyongyang </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Not To Rule Out Ties With Pyongyang </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1305141394 Taipei CNA in English 1337 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1305141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 13 (CNA) -- Taipei won't rule out the 
possibility of setting up ties or an official channel of 
communication with Pyongyang while it tries to develop a 
substantive relationship with Seoul, Prime Minister Lien Chan 
said Friday. [13 May] 
  Lien, answering a question put to him by Legislator Parris 
Chang of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party during an 
interpellation session at the Legislative Yuan, said ties with 
North Korea would still be considered although the ROC and South 
Korea have been trying to rebuild their relationship since they 
broke off formal ties in 1992, when Seoul switched recognition 
to Beijing. 
  Meanwhile, in a bid to respond to the market diversification 
policy set by the goverment, the China external trade 
development council has decided to send a trade delegation to 
North Korea to enhance bilateral economic ties, the Ministry of 
Economic Affairs said. 
  Bilateral trade between Taiwan and North Korea totaled just 
U.S.$7 million last year, with Pyongyang enjoying a surplus with 
Taiwan. Taiwan exports to North Korea are mainly shoe parts and 
metal molds, while North Korean imports here are largely 
agricultural and textile products, Lin Yi-fu, deputy director of 
the Board of Foreign Trade, said. 
  Currently, Mainland China and Cuba are the only two markets 
with which local traders are not allowed to do business since 
the government lifted the trade ban with North Korea in 1992, 
Lin added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

