<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation To Begin Tariff-Reduction Talks in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegation To Begin Tariff-Reduction Talks in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605115594 Taipei CNA in English 0804 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By P. C. Tang and Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, May 16 (CNA) -- A Taiwan trade mission, led 
by Vice Economic Affairs Minister Sheu Ke-sheng, arrived in 
Geneva Sunday [15 May] for the May 77-19 meeting of the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) working party on Taiwan's 
membership in the World Trade Organization. 
  Taiwan will also hold bilateral tariff talks with a number 
of 
nations while in Geneva, including Canada, which is expected to 
ask Taiwan to cut tariffs on more than 800 items. 
Director-General Huang Yen-chao will represent Taiwan during 
the talks with Canada. 
  Delegation members will hold talks with the European Union 
and Switzerland on May 17 and May 19 respectively, and Taiwan is 
expected to meet with representatives from Colombia, Mexico, and 
Korea on May 20. 
  The delegation will also exchange views with South Africa, 
Chile, and Australia during the three days of meetings. 
  So far, Taiwan has held tariff reduction negotiations with 
the United States, Australia, New Zealand, Chile, Turkey, South 
Africa, Hungary, The Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia, and Japan. 
  Bilateral tariff talks with GATT contracting parties are 
considered vital to Taiwan's smooth entry into the Geneva-based 
world trade regulating body. 
  Taiwan was accepted as a GATT observer in September 1992 and 
is expected to become a full member by the end of this year. 

</TEXT>

