<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Council To Help Develop Regional Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Council To Help Develop Regional Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605113694 Taipei CNA in English 0823 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 16 (CNA) -- The Council for Economic 
Planning and Development (CEPD) Monday [15 May] announced an 
eight-point plan to help the government develop Taiwan into an 
Asia-Pacific regional operations center. 
  If the proposals are not implemented in time, a CEPD 
official 
said, Taiwan will waste its "blue chips," which are integral to 
Taiwan's regional operations center bid. 
  The "blue chips" include an exceptionally good geographical 
position, a lively and diversified domestic market, and an 
industrious and capable labor force, the official said. 
  In its plan, the CEPD said Taiwan should focus on becoming a 
regional air transport hub to promote its regional operations 
center bid. 
  The CEPD added that the ports of Kaohsiung, Keelung and 
Taichung should be refurbished and an island-wide transportation 
system should be developed. The government should also work to 
improve Taiwan's Postal and Telecommunication Systems, as well 
as living standards, the plan said. 
  The CEPD further recommended the government reassess its 
land 
policy, and accelerate development of high technology industries. 
  Rounding out the plan are calls to boost cultural and 
recreational development, the official said. 

</TEXT>

