<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Flood Control Projects Launched in Nanjing, Anhui </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Flood Control Projects Launched in Nanjing, Anhui </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1505075894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0701 GMT 15 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1505075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nanjing, May 15 (XINHUA) -- The building of a canal 
has started in Pizhou City in east China's Jiangsu Province, for 
discharging floodwaters from the Yihe, Shuhe and Sihe Rivers, 
all tributaries of the Huaihe River. 
  The three rivers flow over an area of 78,000 sq [square] km 
in southern Shandong Province and northern Jiangsu Province, a 
region which is a major supplier of grain and coal in east China. 
  Government sources said the completion of the project will 
raise the canal's flood-discharge capacity to 5,500 cu m [cubic 
meters] per second. 
  The project, part of the national program to control 
flooding 
on the Huaihe River, will cost more than one billion yuan, which 
will be financed by Jiangsu and Shandong Provinces, said the 
sources. 
  Meanwhile, another flood control project was also started in 
Guoyang County, Anhui Province, on the Baohuihe River, another 
tributary of the Huaihe River with a drainage area of 2,930 sq 
km. 
  The project will involve the dredging of the river channel 
and the building of locks, bridges and pumping stations on the 
river, which, local sources said, will enable the area to resist 
severe floods. 
  The project is supported by a national agricultural 
development fund. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

