<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   PWC Discusses SAR Passports, Other Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PWC Discusses SAR Passports, Other Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1805004294 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1027 
GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1805004294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 17 May (XINHUA) -- The fourth meeting of 
the social and security affairs panel under the Preliminary 
Working Committee [PWC] of the Preparatory Committee of the Hong 
Kong Special Administrative Region [SAR] ended in Beijing today. 
The meeting mainly discussed issues such as preparatory work 
regarding the design and issuance of the PRC's Hong Kong SAR 
passports, as well as issues pertaining to Hong Kong's social 
welfare, such as public housing and the retirement security 
system. 
  While discussing the issuance of Hong Kong SAR passports, 
PWC 
members noted: This task is of great importance to ensuring the 
freedom of entry and exit for Hong Kong residents, to 
strengthening Hong Kong's economic relations and trade with 
other countries and regions, and to maintaining Hong Kong's 
status as an international financial center. The members 
proposed: Hong Kong SAR passports should embody the spirit of 
"one country, two systems," and they should be issued in strict 
accordance with the Basic Law. To enable Hong Kong residents to 
use SAR passports on 1 July 1997, we should make advance 
preparations for the design, printing, and issuance of such 
passports. The members added: Our government will take active 
diplomatic actions with other countries and regions regarding 
mutual visa exemption arrangements for SAR passports; this is 
particularly important. They also noted: Besides SAR 
passports, preparations should also be made regarding SAR travel 
documents. 
  While discussing public housing policy that has a major 
bearing on Hong Kong's welfare, the panel decided to set up a 
public housing research group. To broadly canvass opinions in 
all quarters, some public figures in Hong Kong will be invited 
to serve as advisers to the research group. The panel also 
discussed the retirement security system. 
  The meeting was held in Beijing 16-17 May. 

</TEXT>

